story: In May of next year I will be running the Edinburgh Half Marathon in support of Macmillan Cancer Support.A number of years ago I was ill, and was very grateful to have the support of this incredible charity.I was off work for a protracted period of time and I received a grant from Macmillan which went a long way to relieving some of the financial pressure this caused.Now, I am a doctor working in the Northern Ireland Cancer Centre.I see the support provided by Macmillan to patients on the wards every single day.Financial support with grants and assistance claiming welfare, emotional support with Information and Support Centres and the Macmillan Cancer Support Line and practical support from Macmillan nurses.Macmillan is a charity I am very grateful to have the opportunity to support.Please help me reach this ambitious fund-raising target!

story:
As some of you already know, we have recently lost a very special Nan, Mum & Wife recently. 

I’m sure everyone who knew her would know how wonderfully amazing she was, how she always gave the best hugs & was always the life of any party or family gathering 💛 

Thank you so much on behalf of all of us for the amazing flowers, cards & lovely messages we’ve received. 

The funeral will be a private family service on Tuesday the 3rd of November. But once all COVID restrictions are lifted, we will be holding a more fitting celebration of her life with all welcome. 

We have opened donations to the Macmillan Cancer Support & any little donations will be warmly received.

story:
We’re going bald!

When I was diagnosed with breast cancer a few months ago, one of the first responses I had from my sister-in-law was: ‘if you lose your hair, I’ll brave the shave!’

So here I am, facing 18 weeks of chemotherapy and the certain knowledge that I will be losing all of my hair...as is she...😂

The very brave and very beautiful Kelly Harding will be Braving the Shave on Friday 13th November so that I don’t have to go bald on my own.  I’ll be doing it too of course...it’s my choice when my hair goes!

We will be raising money for Macmillan Cancer Support who provide emotional, physical and financial support from diagnosis through treatment and beyond with all types of cancer. To have this support when you need it most really is invaluable. 

In addition we will both be donating our hair to The Little Princess Trust, a charity that provides free, real-hair wigs for children and young cancer sufferers experiencing the devastating effects of hair loss.  

Cancer affects us all at some point in our lives.  Please show your support and dig deep...I don’t think I could be as brave as Kelly if I wasn’t going to lose my hair anyway!!  

And while you’re at it, check your tits and other bits...it could save your life.

Thank you xx

https://www.macmillan.org.uk/

https://www.littleprincesses.org.uk/

story:
As if 2020 couldn't be shitty enough with a global pandemic, earlier this month I was diagnosed with bowel cancer which has decided to take a first class trip to my liver and lungs! I am waiting to see which treatment I will be blessed with, in the meantime I thought I would keep myself busy and focus on something else rather than the shitshow my family are facing. No doom and gloom allowed!

I have taken inspiration from the twins at Coppafeel Charity and have decided to undertake a 5 hour bounce off.  The event coincides with the final of TGBBO, so my children and I will be channelling Bake Off vibes as we bounce (expect tunes ,glitter and Paul Hollywood masks). We will be bouncing on trampolines for 5 hours and streaming it live on Instagram - pray for my pelvic floor. Everyone who donates will also be entered in a raffle to win some fabulous prizes. 

We are encouraging friends, family and facebook stalkers to join in the madness on the 28/11/2020. You can bounce, skip or jump for as long as your bladder dictates! 

**HEALTH WARNING** if you already pee when laughing or sneezing then this probably isn't for you. No worries you can just donate instead. The charity sector has suffered greatly due to Covid-19, so any donations would be thoroughly appreciated, no matter how small.

Finally if anyone could lend us a mini trampoline that would be fab, or space hoppers it is!!

Macmillan Cancer Support is here to help everyone with cancer live life as fully as they can, providing physical, financial and emotional support. So whatever cancer throws your way, they're right right there with you. Lets help Macmillan continue to provide vital support through 2020. 

Thanks for your support,

Cheryl (aka Star Bouncer)

xx

story:
Isobel Clason

Grangemouth

1928 - 2020


Peacefully at her home in Grangemouth on 18th October 2020.  Isobel (nee Mackay) aged 92 years.  Beloved wife of the late Bill, much loved mum of Charles, Christine and William and a dear mother in law to Anne, John and Deborah, gran, great gran, sister in law, auntie and friend who will be sadly missed by all who knew and loved her.

She lived for those she loved and those she loved remember. 

Due to current funeral restrictions the family ask that if anyone is so inclined, they make funeral donations to the British Heart Foundation in honour of Isobel using this Just Giving page.

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge weve faced in our 60 year history. And its led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, weve never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into groundbreaking science and support for the people who need us most. Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the worlds biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we cant drop the ball now.

story: Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

story:
Help us raise enough to support 12 brand new guide dogs this Christmas! 

During December hundreds of our fundraising dogs across the UK would usually be out and about wagging their tails and meeting you at supermarket and street collections, Christmas fairs and festive coffee mornings. Our four-legged fundraisers support the 400+ fundraising groups across the UK from Glasgow to Plymouth and everywhere in between.

Due to the current situation, most of our fundraising groups will not be out collecting this festive season, and our four-legged fundraisers will be very much missed! We hope you will do your bit and help us as we aim to raise enough for 12 new guide dog partnerships! Heres how you can join in: 

	Donate £12 and share our posts across social media nominating a friend, family member or colleague to  get involved

story:
Almost two million people in the UK are living with sight loss that has a significant impact on their daily lives. Of those, around 180,000 rarely leave their homes alone and lead lonely, isolated lives. 

Guide Dogs works for a world where people with sight loss are never left out of life, for a world where being blind or partially sighted is not what defines you. A world with enough support to make the challenges of sight loss no barrier to fulfilling hopes and dreams.

story: I am taking on the Brighton Marathon 2021 for GOSH! Every day brings new challenges at Great Ormond Street Hospital (GOSH). Every day, 618 children and young people from across the UK arrive. Every day, doctors and nurses battle the most complex illnesses, and the brightest minds come together to achieve pioneering medical breakthroughs. And every day is a chance for you to make a difference. This extraordinary hospital has always depended on charitable support to give seriously ill children the best chance to fulfil their potential. A better future for seriously ill children starts here.

Established in Birmingham (UK),  ProjectTOM - a voluntary, unfunded, grassroot,  #ActsOfKindness  non-profit group since 2008 - where everyone is unpaid, donates their spare time and effort on top of their full-time jobs or studies - has raised over £47,000 GBP for charitable causes both at home and abroad with over 71,300 beneficiaries. story:
Hi All,

October is Breast Cancer Awareness Month, so I thought I would chop my locks to help raise vital funds for Cancer Research UK.

I realise that this is a small gesture, but many small gestures add up to something much larger, so I thought I would play my little part.

I'm not going to shave my head Sinead O'Connor style (I am not that brave!), but I will be chopping off enough to allow me to donate my hair to the Little Princess Trust so that they can hopefully turn it into a wig for someone who needs it. 

Medical research charities have taken a massive hit throughout the pandemic, so if you could support by giving just a little it would be much appreciated. 

Thank you!! 

Ailsa

story:
Our beloved Bobby lost his battle with cancer on Monday 26th October at 5:01pm at 64 years young. 

In light of corona virus and limited attendance at funerals we are aware that people may want to pay their respects in a different way. 

Cancer is a devastating disease that has affected everyone at some point in their lives, raising even a little money in Bobbys memory may help someone else in the future from going through the same thing. 

All our love

Carol, Sean, Kirsty, Jake, George, Leigh, Calley, Mark, Dan & Dandy xxx

story:
As some of you will know 3 years ago my Dad was diagnosed with Prostate Cancer and endured weeks of radiotherapy but unfortunately it cannot be fully cured. Since then he has also been diagnosed with Lung Cancer which again cannot be cured but is treatable. I am so proud of how well he is dealing with it all but I wanted to do something to show him how proud I am and to hopefully help others in similar situations 💕

Therefore I will be cycling the equivalent of a marathon (26.2 miles) everyday in November on my spin bike.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

This year YSJ Kats have decided to raise money for Cancer Research. One of our charity events is going to be a Christmas raffle with 100% of the money raised being donated to this worthy charity. There is some amazing prizes to be won including; A bottle of gin from York Gin, an afternoon tea for 2 at Novotel and a meal voucher for 2 at Revolution York. 

Every step we make towards beating cancer relies on every pound that is donated to this charity. Unfortunately, due to Covid-19 their research has had to be put on pause but we would like to help them get back on track and help beat cancer. 

How to purchase raffle tickets:

1. Make a payment through our Just Giving page (tickets are £1 per strip). Please remember to put your name so that we can confirm payments or take a screenshot of the confirmation once you've paid. 

2. Message either Chelsea Fisher (YSJ Kats Charity Officer) or YSJ cheerleading on Instagram stating how many strips you would like. 

3. We will then send you a photo of your tickets and we will put your tickets into a bucket ready to be drawn. 

The raffle will be drawn on 2nd December. Thank you so much for your continued support and good luck x

story:
Every year, cancer impacts the lives of too many people and most of us have lost someone dear to it or know someone who did. 

To raise money for Cancer Research UK and help find a way to beat cancer once and for all, we're hosting a fun quiz night on Thursday 3 December.

You will have the chance to show off your knowledge on a range of subjects (and obscure fun facts!) guided by our amazing host for the night, James Stevenson! 

Ready to take on the challenge? Make your donation to earn your place! 

(Suggested donation £5, but all donations are welcome!)

eventName: In memory of John Meurig Morris
story:
Sadly on Sunday 25th October 2020 Our Wonderful, Kind, Big hearted John passed away. The Marie Curie nurses that were with him for his final hours cared for him so dignified and kept him comfortable and pain free in his final moments. We would like to show our appreciation to them by donating in his Memory and we will never be able to thank them enough for looking after our beloved John. 

He gave so much to so many all of his life and he will be greatly missed by everyone that knew him.

Thank you so much for your kind donation 

xxxxx

charity.registrationNumber: 207994 (England & Wales) and SC038731 (Scotland)
story:
Tony was an Allied Parts original working with us from his apprenticeship, seen him become more of a family member than a colleague. He'd light up a room when he walked in, would do anything for anyone (never frightened to wind up his pals for laughs!) He became friends with everyone...  it was very hard not to love T! 

After many years battling cancer he sadly lost his fight earlier this year, his last few months were spent in the Marie Curie hospice where the team done everything they could to make sure he was cared for and as comfortable as possible so now is our chance to do something to say thank you and give back to them in his memory. 

Movember is a great cause which works to increase the awareness for male cancer. We have a list of guys willing to participate to let those moustache's grow to raise both money and awareness. We will also be taking cash donations if you would rather donate that way and will have other fund raising activities on to help us raise as much as we can!  

If you would like to donate please do so, there is no minimum or recommended donation as everything we can raise will all go to the hospice to help others just like Tony, 

Thank you x

story:
This page is for those who wish to donate to the RNLI in Owain's memory.

RNLI volunteers work tirelessly to rescue those in trouble at sea, and we are grateful for their efforts to recover Owain.

At the end of the fundraising events, in honour of your donations, I will add Owain's name to the RNLI's "Launch a Memory" campaign. It will be added to the hull of a lifeboat, where it will sail the seas west of Ireland for at least the next 10 years.

Clare (Owain's sister)

Steve loved his cruise holidays, sailing around the world always looking out for dolphins and loved to watch the ocean from his balcony on the ship. 

We have chosen this charity because Steve always supported the RNLI and we would like to continue to raise funds in his name.

story:
Too many people are still drowning. More than ever we need the RNLI’s help. As a charity, the RNLI depends on our donations so it can go on saving lives and keeping us and our loved ones safe. 

RNLI lifesavers are our lifeline. They’re the lifeboat crews who provide 24-hour search and rescue right around the UK and Ireland. The lifeguards keeping watch on 240 of the busiest beaches in the UK and Channel Islands. And the RNLI safety teams and educators working tirelessly to stop people getting into trouble in the first place.

Thank you.

charity.description:
We’re the world’s leading independent conservation organisation. And we’re building a future where people and nature thrive together. 

That’s why we’re passionate about sharing the planet’s resources more sustainably, tackling climate change and protecting endangered wildlife.
charity.name: WWF-UK
story:
Welcome to our page! We're committing to helping to keep our planet running and we want everyone to get involved. Our premise is simple, we want to run all the way around our planet. To help us achieve this, what we ask is that you run one kilometer, donate £1 and share your experience with at least one person, it's that simple!

Our goal therefore is the full 40,075km round the circumference of Earth and by the time we've made it around we'll have raised £40,075 for WWF, our chosen charity. It's a long way but we'd love for you to join us and be a part of this journey. Follow us on Instagram for updates and to share your photos from your runs @keep_our_planet_running

WWF do some amazing work all around the world for wilderness preservation, conservation and reducing our impact on the natural world. For more information on their latest projects check out the website https://www.wwf.org.uk/ or watch David Attenborough: A Life on Our Planet, produced by the WWF.

But we would hate to think we were being restrictive, if you have that urge to run further, donate more or share endlessly we would love to see it. But also don't feel like you have to run, get together for a walk with friends. Just make sure to enjoy this time out in nature and appreciate our wonderful planet! 

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

story: IF YOU GO DOWN TO THE WOODS TODAY... You might notice theres less wildlife than there used to be. Thats because half of all UK species are in decline were losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate. By taking part in The Big Winter Wander, you and your friends and family can reconnect with our country's beautiful wildlife and help protect it. The funds you raise will help us campaign to protect wildlife here, and around the world. Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now its our time to give back.

charity.registrationNumber: 1072612 (England & Wales) and SC043677 (Scotland)
story:
Thank you for taking the time to visit my just giving page.

This year I decided to take on the challenge of the London Marathon in October 2021. To that end, I realized I needed to practice running around London and getting a sense of the city that I live in, whilst also allowing myself to be the tourist I know that I am. I chose to run the Royal Parks Half Marathon, as I believe that it would give myself an introduction to long-distance running and afford myself the best possible opportunity to meet Prince Charles.

I chose to run for UNICEF due to the crucial work that they do each and every day. This work has never been more vital than during the coronavirus pandemic. Now more than ever it crucial to support global charities in order to bring the world together and move forward through this crisis. I implore you to read the stories of the fantastic work that UNICEF does throughout the world. 

Once again thank you for your consideration of donating to UNICEF, and I hope that I will do you all proud in April when I run the Royal Parks Half Marathon.

Reece
